The subject interested the artist so much that he would dedicate several canvases to it. He animatedly depicted fishing boats grounded on the shingle shores, the restlessness of the waves, and people out for a stroll.\u003cbr\u003eIn this study, Monet tightly framed two boats closest to the water. The very simple composition is structured around three horizontals punctuated by the two colored diagonals of the boats.\u003c/p\u003e"]],["//lh3.googleusercontent.com/ci/AEwo86c_-fnhKce6TiBndmS3Y1j0QqjoQjCj7Vwtx0EY6lLGFGGp1ncUwhP7XgJCNhLurKmFt8Piww",null,[null,"\u003cp\u003eLike Monet and Eugène Boudin before him, Auburtin painted the boats lined up on the beach of Étretat. His art, which was developed at the crossroads of different influences, stemmed from his admiration for the great masters of Japanese printmaking.\u003c/p\u003e"]],["//lh3.googleusercontent.com/ci/AEwo86fe8Wlcycxm2jh7i53gNSBkWt2AviiOSon7x5RGbqYkTG46XQg_vYNbzMXyiS_rVP4KqphYeQ",null,[null,"\u003cp\u003eMonet returned to Étretat with his family in September 1885.\u003cbr\u003eHe hurriedly started on 51 canvases, many of which would be completed at his Giverny workshop. Twenty-four depicted the Porte d’Aval and the rock needle (L\u0026#39;Aiguille), six depicted the Porte d\u0026#39;Amont, and ten were of boats on the beach. A further six were of the Manneporte, one of Antifer, and four of hinterland landscapes.\u003cbr\u003eMonet also produced canvases that had been started during previous stays. He returned, for the last time, for a few days in February 1886.\u003c/p\u003e"]],["//lh3.googleusercontent.com/ci/AEwo86cFW5_-eL97pPvIZw8Ib5YiE1yrX4Ia_09AhDbcHfgLBbgpZ_O0ZJcgTYTJMbh4naLponvPUMs",null,[null,"\u003cp\u003eIn 1886, in an article entitled \u0026quot;La vie d’un paysagiste\u0026quot;, writer Guy de Maupassant introduced Monet to readers of the periodical Gil Blas. He described the artist just as he had met him—on the cliffs of Étretat one year earlier, capturing \u0026quot;in a few brush strokes, the falling sunbeams or the passing cloud.[…] I saw him catching a glittering fall of light on the white cliff and painting it with a flow of yellow tones that were strangely giving an amazing and fleeting impression of that elusive and blinding dazzle. In truth, he was no longer a painter, but a hunter.\u0026quot; (Guy de Maupassant, \u0026quot;La vie d’un paysagiste,\u0026quot; in \u0026quot;Gil Blas,\u0026quot; September 28, 1886, p. 1).\u003c/p\u003e"]],["//lh3.googleusercontent.com/ci/AEwo86dpDAOul0MSGE1_Oa3JJ6ct-kIeJhwFefvcEyBj1YbyQDFVddKSjacjIG0Uqfe8_u80XmBfzIfV",null,[null,"\u003cp\u003eAuburtin followed in Monet\u0026#39;s footsteps, choosing similar sites in Normandy. His 1939 works and first major public success was a mural titled Switzerland: \"Vacation Land of the People\" was commissioned and displayed for the national exhibition in Zürich.\nThe Hans Erni Museum, situated in the grounds of the Swiss Museum of Transport in Lucerne, contains a large collection of artwork, he also designed ceramics and theatre costumes and sets. He did the art for Swiss bank notes, in the 1940s but, after the notes were already printed they were never published, because a member of the State Council of Lucerne criticized that Erni was deemed as a communist. However, Erni was never a member of any political party. But why does this shape reappear time and time again in building design?\u003c/p\u003e"]],["","Stonehenge - UK",[null,"\u003cp\u003ePerhaps the most famous circular structure of them all, Stonehenge dates to somewhere between 3000 and 2000 BCE. Most famously created by Rabbi Loew in 16th century Prague, the golem was intended to protect the Jewish people against attacks.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eEmily D. Bilski, a curator and scholar in nineteenth- and twentieth-century art and cultural history, writes:\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u0026quot;The Golem, the artificially created human of Jewish tradition has long been evoked as a metaphor for artificial intelligence by scientists, philosophers, writers, and artists.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eThe motivations and methods for creating a golem, as well as the golem’s actions once it has been brought to life, have provided powerful analogies for the potential risks and benefits of creating artificial intelligence.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eThe word ‘golem’ occurs once in the Bible, ‘Thine eyes did see my golem...’ (Psalm 139:16), where it denotes an unformed substance, something embryonic. According to Talmudic commentaries, these words were spoken by Adam to God, and ‘golem’ was understood as the physical form of man before acquiring a soul. This innate connection between the first human and a golem inspired writers and artists beginning in the nineteenth century to view the golem as our doppelgänger, a concept that can be seen mirrored in AI developments and in our desire to create ever-more human-looking robots and synthetic humans.\u0026quot;\u003c/p\u003e"]],["//lh3.googleusercontent.com/ci/AEwo86eH4UHhtunRx5IQFLKIBmRxeOtTskGPv90AwJqB3QKBWzenR6tbSNJ2uAcWe_FmUO_r1z_FvA",null,[null,"\u003cp\u003e\u0026quot;Each of the many manifestations of the golem – in literature, theatre, film, visual art, or popular culture – has reflected the concerns of their creators and the anxieties of the times in which they lived, whether the increased brutality of technological warfare, political movements run amok, the threat of nuclear annihilation, or scientific advances in biotechnology, AI, and big data. Both the golem story and Frankenstein have been understood as expressing the ‘horrors’ that science and technology can wreak.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eYet it is the golem that underscores the ambivalent relationship we have with scientific and technological progress.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eIn this regard, the scientist seeks to benefit humanity, just as the goal of the rabbis was to rescue Jews threatened by violence; therefore, any resulting danger is an unintended consequence. It is this dialectical nature of the golem – at once saviour and destroyer – that offers fertile comparisons with AI, and has inspired writers, filmmakers, and artists to interpret this archetypical.\u0026quot;\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cb\u003eAt its core, the golem motif explores the mystery and power of the creative act.\u003c/b\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eEmily D. In a self-improving cycle, rapidly building machines that are so capable and intelligent that humans cannot control them. I don’t personally know if this is a reasonable hypothesis. history</div></span><h3 class="icXnic" title="On this day in 1909, Hans Erni was born">On this day in 1909, Hans Erni was born</h3><h4 class="gDqesd" title="Hans Erni was a Swiss graphic designer, painter, illustrator, engraver and sculptor.
Born in Lucerne, the third of eight siblings, to a cabin cruiser engineer, he studied art at the Académie Julian in Paris and later in Berlin, and admired artists such as Pablo Picasso and Georges Braque.
He is known for having illustrated postage stamps, his lithographs for the Swiss Red Cross, his participation on the Olympic Committee as well as his activism. His 1939 works and first major public success was a mural titled Switzerland: &quot;Vacation Land of the People&quot; was commissioned and displayed for the national exhibition in Zürich.
The Hans Erni Museum, situated in the grounds of the Swiss Museum of Transport in Lucerne, contains a large collection of artwork, he also designed ceramics and theatre costumes and sets. He did the art for Swiss bank notes, in the 1940s but, after the notes were already printed they were never published, because a member of the State Council of Lucerne criticized that Erni was deemed as a communist. However, Erni was never a member of any political party. In 2004, he was awarded the honorary citizenship of the city of Lucerne.">Hans Erni was a Swiss graphic designer, painter, illustrator, engraver and sculptor.
Born in Lucerne, the third of eight siblings, to a cabin cruiser engineer, he studied art at the Académie Julian in Paris and later in Berlin, and admired artists such as Pablo Picasso and Georges Braque.
He is known for having illustrated postage stamps, his lithographs for the Swiss Red Cross, his participation on the Olympic Committee as well as his activism. His 1939 works and first major public success was a mural titled Switzerland: &quot;Vacation Land of the People&quot; was commissioned and displayed for the national exhibition in Zürich.
The Hans Erni Museum, situated in the grounds of the Swiss Museum of Transport in Lucerne, contains a large collection of artwork, he also designed ceramics and theatre costumes and sets. He did the art for Swiss bank notes, in the 1940s but, after the notes were already printed they were never published, because a member of the State Council of Lucerne criticized that Erni was deemed as a communist. However, Erni was never a member of any political party. In 2004, he was awarded the honorary citizenship of the city of Lucerne.</h4><div class="v71GJc">Learn more</div></div></span></a><div class="cCNe0" jscontroller="acWgwb" jsaction="JIbuQc:UEmoBd;
